\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 29. B. falcatum} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 237 (1753) (incl. {\i B. exaltatum }Bieb., {\i B. olympicum} Boiss.,{\i  B. parnassicum} Halácsy, {\i B. rossicum} Woronow,{\i  B. sibthorpianum} Sm., {\i B. woronovii} Manden.). Very variable perennial or rarely annual up to 100 cm; stock almost or quite devoid of remains of dead leaves. Basal leaves obovate elliptical, oblong or linear, distinctly petiolate or sessile; veins 5-7; cauline leaves sessile, semi-amplexicaul, lanceolate to linear often falcate. Rays 3-15, filiform. Bracts 2-5, lanceolate to subulate, very unequal; veins 3-5; bracteoles 5, linear-lanceolate, acuminate; veins 3(-5). Fruit 3-6 mm; ridges filiform or more or less winged.{\i  S., C. & E. Europe, extending north-westwards to S. England.} Al Au Be Br Bu Co Cz Ga Ge Gr He Hs Hu It Ju Po Rm Rs(C,W,K,E).
