\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 32. B. spinosum} Gouan,{\i  Obs. Bot.} 8 (1773). Intricately branched, glaucous perennial up to 30 cm; lower part of stems stout, woody, devoid of remains of dead leaves; upper parts of stems dying after fruiting, becoming hard and spinose and persisting for 2-3 years. Basal leaves linear-subulate, scarcely narrowed at base; veins 3-5, conspicuous beneath; cauline similar but smaller, few, remote. Rays 2-7, becoming rigid and spinose after the fruit has been shed. Bracts 2 mm, usually 5, subulate, 1-veined; bracteoles similar to the bracts, but sometimes lanceolate. Fruit 3-4·5 mm, ovoid-oblong; ridges filiform, prominent.{\i  S. & E. Spain.} Hs.
